{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_jellymoss_ver01/data/sn84020657/00279526879/1921022201/0366.xml":{"full_text":"HEARINGS OVER\nON ROAD FUNDS\nFOR TERRITORY\nSteese Ends Fight Before\nSenate Committee\u2014Report\nExpected in Few Days.\nr\nThe fight for increased appropria\ntions for the Alaska Road Commis\ncion's work in the Territory during\nthe next fiscal yer.r before the Sen\nate Committee on Military Affairs\ncame to an end Saturday, according\n*to advices received from Col. James\nG. Steese, President of the Commis\nsion, by Capt. C. S. Ward, Commis\nsion Disbursing Officer. At that\ntime the Committee concluded its\nconsideration of the Alaska Road\nCommission estimates and it Is ex\npected that it will make its report\nto the Senate within a very short\ntime.\nWhat success attended the efforts\nof Col. Steese and those who have\nbeen cooperating with him in ap\npearing before the Senate Commit\ntee is not known as the Committee's\ndecision will not be publicly avail\nable until its report is completed\nand transmitted to the Senate. Col.\nSteese Is optimistic, however, and\nbelieves that a substantial increase\never the amount allowed by the\nHouse will be recommended by the\nSenate Committee and approved by\nthe Senate in passing the measure.\nJn his effort to have the full esti\nmates of the Commission restored\nby the Senate over the $:\u2019>50,000\ngranted by the House, Col. Steese\nwas supported by Alaskan commer\ncial organizations and individuals\nwho telegraphed Senators on the\nCommittee, giving them brief de\nscriptions of transportation condi\ntions and needs in Alaska and urg\ning the fullest possible recognition\nof the Alaska Road Commission's\nestimates as a means of solving the\ntraimportation problems which hin\nder Alaskan development.\nFinal action by the Senate is ex\npected to be taken in a few days.\nCol. Steese plans to leave Washing\nton shortly thereafter and arrive in\nJuneau about March 20.\nVIOLENT ERUPTION\nOF POPOCATEPETL\nAOAIN THREATENS\nfamous Volcano Back of\njVfexico City Throwing Out\nColumns of Gas.\n(Continued From Page One.)\naccompaniment of the violent earth\nquakes. The volcano is said to be\nof the type that, as a rule, <loe3\nnot emit molten lava, but ejects\npumice and volcanic ash.\nThe shocks began shortly before\nmidnight on December 9 and for\nthree hours were almost continuous,\nterrifying the population, most of\nwhich are Indians. The most vio\nlent quake lasted 20 seconds. The\nwhole region vibrated intermittently\nduring the next five days.\nEntire Hills Razed.\nEntire hills were razed and many;\ncattle were killed by falling trees.!\nMuch damage was done to small!\nbuildings in the town of Pucon.j\nwhich is a port of entry from Ar-j\ngeatina; parts of the international\nhighway to Argentina were de\nstroyed; two lumber mlils were\nwrecked and a third was totally\nburied under a mass of earth and\nrock.\nl^ake Vlllarica rose five feet later\nsubsiding while Lake Cuburga is\nreported to have sunk 15 feet. The\nTurbio River, which had its source\non the side of Mount Vlllarica dis\nappeared entirely and the Tancura\nRiver, which flows in the valley\nbearing that name, shrunk to half\nits normal flow.\nThe district affected is one of\nthe most picturesque in Chile. Eat\nest advices said Vlllarica had\nquieted.\n1 \"i\nEATON CRANE\nAND PIKE\nFINE\nSTATIONERY\nBUTLER, MAURO\nDRUG CO.\n96 Front Street\nPostoffice Substation No. I\nt\n\u20224\nPRESIDENT-ELECT\nSPRINGS SURPRISE\nIN CABINET SLATE\n\nEdwin Denby, Detroit Law\nyer and Former Congress\nmen to Be Navy Secretary.\n(Continued From Page One.)\nBarr Baker, identified with Herbert\nHoover in European relief work,\ntoday declared that Mr. Hoover had\nnot as yet received any offer from\nPresident-elect Harding of the post\nof Secretary of Commerce.\nI Mr. Baker declared his friends be\nlieve that the Department of Com\nmerce offers no such field for scr\nvice to a man of Mr. Hoover's at\ntainments as service in stations with\nwhich he is now identified.\nDenby\u2019s Brother Alaskan.\nWyeth Denby, a brother of Ed\nwin Denby, the new Secretary of\nthe Navy, was a former resident of\nJuneau. He was interested in min\ning and resided here for a half\ndozen years prior to his departure\nin 1908. After leaving Juneau he\nresided tn Washington and British\nColumbia, making his residence at\ndifferent times at Seattle and Ho\nquiam, Wash., and Vancouver, B. C.\nEdwin, Wyeth und Charles Denby\nare sons of the late Charles Denbv,\nwho served as United States Min\nlster to China during the first\nCleveland administration. Edwin\nDenby is a member of the Detroit\nlaw firm of Chamberlain, Denby,\nWebster and Kenedy, and treasurer\nof the Hupp Motor Car Company\nand the Denby Motor Truck Com\npany, of which liis borther Charles\nDenby is Vice-President. His wife\nwas Miss Marion Tlntrber, sister of\nPresident Cleveland's private secre\ntary' during his second term. His\nbrother, Charles Denby, was Chief\nClerk in the State Department dur\ning the second Cleveland adminis\ntration. He is 60 years of age, a|\nnative of Evansville, Ind., and has\nresided in Detroit since 1896. He:\nwas a Representative in Congress\nin the 69th, 60th and 61st Con\ngresses. Although of a Democratic\nfamily, he left the party with the\nascendency of Bryan In 1896.\nCERTIFICATE ISSUED\nBURROUGHS BY BOARD\n\nThe Territorial Canvassing Board\nat a session hold yesterday issued j\na certificate of Infection to 1^ W. I\nBurroughs, Republican us a Repre\nsentative in .the Territorial Legis\nlature. At a session of the Board\nheld last Saturday afternoon at the\noffice of Gov. Thomas Riggs, Chair\nman, the returns from Fortuna Ledge\nand Willow Crook, the precincts at\nMarshall on the Yukon River, were\ncanvassed. They gave Burroughs 11\nvotes and Victor A. Jullen, his near\nest opponent 2. Burroughs was al\nready leading Julian by five votes,\nand this addition gave him a lead oi\n14. A telegram was received from\nClerk of the Court Thomas McGann\nof Nome saying that no election had\nbeen held at Bethel. The only other\nSecond Division precinct that had not\nbeen heard from was Kotzebue, but\nthat precinct lias less than 14 votes,\nso the certificate was ordered issued\nto Burroughs. All the other certifi\ncates of election had been previously\nissued.\niVan A. Sutherland's majority for\nDelegate to Congress was reduced\nby 13 votes as the result of the re\nturns from Fortuna Ledge and Wil\nlow Creek, and John Rustgard's\nmajority for Attorney General was\nincreased by five votes.\nAt Fortuna Ledge the vote for\nDelegate was: Grigsby 13, Suther\nland 3; Murphy 10, Rustgard 3. At\nWillow Creek it was: Grigsby 9,\nSutherland 6; Murphy 2. Rustgard\n13.\nSharp Declines in Fur\nPrices at Big Auction\nST. LOUIS, Feb. 22 \u2014Sharp de\nclines since the lust sale in May,\u2019\nfeatured all offerings at the Inter-1\nnational Fur Exchange Auction!\nSale here today, with the exception\nof X2,000 marten furs which showed\nan increase of ten per cent. Blue\nand white foxes were fifteen per\nI cent lower while seal pelts showed\nthe greatest decline, averaging a\ndrop of forty-five per cent.\nCABLE SERVICE RESTORED\nThe cable between Valdez and\nI Sitka, after three months' interrup\ntion, has been repaired by the Cable\nship Burnside, according to infor\nmation received at the local U, S\nCable Office. The Sitka-Valdez line\nwas interrupted early last Novem\nber by a severe earthquake shock\nand has been out of commission\nsince that time.\nThe Burnside, while repairing the\nbreak in November, encountered\nlough weather and was forced to\nl put back to Seattle for repairs\nAfter being there for several weeks\njche was restored to duty and again\ncame North to the cable break.\nStorms again delayed the work to\na considerable extent The Burnside\nIs now at Haines and Will leave\nfrom there for the South in a\nshort time.\nWOMAN EXONERATED IN HORTON MURDER.\nMrs. John Walter Brooks has been exonerated of complicity In the\nkilling of Lieuteraut Floyd Horton, who was murdered by auto bandits\nin New York city. In the picture with Mrs. Brooks are John Kavanagh,\nwho was also exonerated, and (in centre) Detective Wilson.\ni _ i 1\nBusiness Depression\nNear End, Says\n1 Secretary of Commerce\nI I\nST. LOUIS, Mo., Feb. 22.\u2014 1\nTlie base of business depression\nhas been reached. Secretary of\nCommerce .1. W. Alexander de\nclared yesterday in a speoc h\nbefore the International Fur Kx\nchange, which yesterday opened\nits annual winter auction sale\nwith millions of pelts offered\nand more than 500 buyers from\nall parts of the world in attend\nance.\nSuggesting optimism as a\ncure for commercial ills, the\nSecretary declared \u201cour flnan\neial condition is essentially\nsound.\u201d\ni _Li\nDISTRICT COURT IS\nCALLED FOR SESSION\nTOMORROW AFTERNOON\nThe United States District Court\nv/ill be called tomorrow afternoon\nat 2 o\u2019clock, all jurymen, both\ngrand and petit jurors, being re\nquested to report at that hour.\nlT. S. Clerk of the Court J. W. Bell\nreceived a wireless message this\nafternoon from United Stutes Dis-!'\ntrirt Judge Robert W. Jennings,\naboard the Princess Mary, that i\nawing to a snow storm he would\nnot be able to reach Juneau Wed-\ni.osday morning in time for the ses-\n,iun at 10 o'clock and to adjourn\ncourt until 2 o'clock Wednesday\nafternoon.\nAir Mail Pilot Killed j\nIn Attempt at Record\nSAN FRANCISCO, Feb. 22.\u2014Capt.\nW. F. Lewis pilot in the air mail scr\nvice between Reno and Salt' Lakt\nCity, was killed near Elko, Nev..!\ntoday when his plane fell several\nhundred feet. Capt. Lewis with I\nothers in the mail service was cn\ngaged in an attempt to lower tin\nrecord between San Francisco and\nNew York when the accident o<\ncured.\n\nPhorphorus Bombs Used\nAgainst Japanese, Charge\nLOS ANGELES, Cal., Feb. 22 I\nTwo attempts to destroy buildings\nhere occupied by Japanese through\nthe use of phosphorus bombs have\nbeen made recently, tbe bombs ;!e j\npurtment of llie fire prevention bu j\nreau announced today. Japanese\nhave asked the Department of Justice\nto investigate.\nTranscontinental Flyer\nForced to Land in Texas\n\nDALLAS, Tex., Feb. 23.\u2014Lieut\nWilliam Coney, who left San Diego, i\nCalifornia, last night in an attempt\nto make a 24 hour coast to coast;\nHip lit was forced to land this morn\ning near Uronte, Texas, because 01\nengine trouble.\n\n100,000 Rent Payers in\nChicago Launch \u201cStrike\u201d\nCHICAGO, Fob. 22\u2014A tenants!\nstrike was launched by tile Chicago\nTenants' Protective Association hero\ntoday and campaign meetings are\nbeing held in all parts of the city,\nit is planned to enlist a hundred\nthousand tenants and refuse to pay\nIncreased rents.\nVilla Hunting Treasure\nIn Mountains of Mexico\n_\nMEXICO CITY, Feb 22.\u2014Fran\ncisco Villu. retired bandit chieftain.\nwith a large body of men is seareh\n1 ins tile mountains of Durango for\nloot buried three ye$rs ago, ac\ncording to travelers arriving here.\nOLD DIGGIN\u2019S WILL\nBE SCENE OF DREDGE\nMINING THIS SEASON\nTV it is probable Minook Creek,\none i-f the first creeks in Interior\nV; ska on which gold was produced\nin prying quantities, will be l)xe\nscene of considerable mining activ\nity tills summer is indicated in a\nI'.'ller received at the office cf the\nTerritorial Secretary from A. F.\nSchmitz, President of the Minook\nDredging Company, Mr. Schmitz\nstated that it was believed that his\ncompany would install a dredge on\nthe creek this season and start ac\ntive opeiations as soon as possible.\nIn its annual report to the Secre\ntary of Alaska, the company claims\nto have more than $1,(100,000 in\nassets consisting of a dredger, thaw\nr. drill and improvements on the\n.round, it also shows that it owns\n10 association claims of 160 acres\ninch on which operations will be\nundertaken. A. T. Itowe, of Hot\nsprings, is Alaska representative of\nbe company.\n-Ui ui/on. V-ICCIV iz> I1I1IC'. IU11~\nLiitl empties into the Yukon River\nt'st oast of Rampart. The first claim\niriu which gold was produced in\nhe Rampart district was situated\nn Mi nook Creek, being worked in\n181)6 by F. S. Langford, though\ntcld Iiad been previously sluiced on\n1 e creek by John Minook, r. Rus\n,i; n hall' breed after whom the\nireek was named.\nOwing to the wide valley of the\nireok. heavy gravel and large\nteam, which made ordinary placer\nnining difficult, a great deal of gold\nlas not been produced on the creek,\nli t it is considered a likely stream\nor dredging operations and there\ns .1 substntial amount of dredging\n\u2022round available.\nMr. Schmitz, writing to Secretary\nb nimcrs, from lies Moines, la.,\n;t;.ted that arrangements had been\npractically concluded for the neces\ni-rv capital to begin operations and\nniters some unforseen obstacle\nirises, a start will be made this\n:cr son.\nPresident Denounced tor\nTreatment of Eugene Debs\nCHICAGO, Feb. 22. Socialist\nParty headquarters issued a state\nmeat here today denouncing Presi\ndent Wilson and the Department uf\nJustice, claiming that Kugene Deb^,\nimprisoned at Atlanta Federal Peni\ntentiary. has been denied the priv\nilege's of the of the penitentiary in\nregards to writing letters and receiv\ning visitors The statement assumes\nthat the order \"which extends even\nto weekly letters to his wife,\u2019 was\nissued at the instance of the Presi\ndent.\nWHO\u2019S* HERE\nMrs. W. H. King, who has been\nvisiting with her son here for the\npad several months, leaves on the1\nNorthwestern for Cordova.\nLouis Hertl, of Kennpcott, who has\nbeen in Juneau for several Weeks,\nleaves for Seward on the Northwest\nern tomorrow.\nThe.o. Brakke. who has not been\nin Southeastern Alaska for the past\n19* years until he came to Juneau\nseveral days ago, is returning to j\nSeward tomorrow on the Northwest-'\nern.\ni ~~-1;\nI STEAMER MOVEMENTS I\nl i\n1\nNow Bound North\n1 NORTHWESTERN is scheduled j\nto arrive here 4 a. m. tomor- J\nI row. j\nPRINCESS MARY scheduled to\narrive here tomorrow noon.\nScheduled Sailing*\nADMIRAL WATSON scheduled\nto leave Seattle Feb. 24.\nSouthbound Sailings\nPRINCESS MARY scheduled tn\nsail southbound Thursday\nI a. m.\n\nFUND FOR GAME\nPROTECTION IS\nGUT FROM BILL\nSenate Eliminates $25,000 in\nSundry Civil Bill\u2014No\nUneasiness Expressed.\nThe item included in the Sundry\nCivil Appropriation Bill providing\nfor $25,000 for the protection of\ngame in .Alaska during the next\nfiscal year was elimiiated entirely\nin the Senate by the adoption ol' the\nCommittee import. The item stricken\nread.: \"Protection of game in Alaska:\nFor carrying out the act entitled\n'An Act for the Protection of Game\nin Alaska, and other purposes,- ap\nproved May 11, 1908, including sal\naries, traveling expenses of game\nwardens and all other necessary ex\npenses, $25,000, to be expended under\nhe direction of the Governor of Ai\nr-ska.\"\nGov. Thomas Riggs said today\nthat while he had received no infor\nmation regarding the matter, he had\nseen notice of the above action in\nthe Congressional Record. He also\nsaid he had no uneasiness over the\nlack of funds for this purpose and\nbelieved it would all be included in\nthe Argicultural Appropriation Bill\nunder the item provided for the Bio\nogical Survey.\nGOTWALS MAKES FAST\nTRIP TO ANCHORAGE;\nRETURNS TO INTERIOR\nMaking a record trip, Maj. J. C.\nGotwals, Engineer Olficcr of the\nAlaska Road Commission, yesterday\narrived in Anchorage, making the\njump from McGrath over Rainy Pass\nb.v the way of Cache Creek to the\nrailroad in nine days, according io\nadvices received at the local com\nmission offices thiig morning. The\ntime is considered excellent In view\nof the light travel over the trail\nused by him, making it heavy and\nhard for sledding.\nMaj. Gotwals plans to remain in\nAnchorage but a short time. He\nwill proceed from there over the\nRroad Pass to Lignite Creek and\nmake a final reconnaissance of the\nproposed routes Into the Kantishna\ndistrict from the railroad, selecting\nthe route over which the wagon\nroad will be constructed, work on\nwhich is expected to start next\nspring.\nAfter making the selection, Maj.\nGotwals will return to his headquar\ntors here, probably arriving about\nthe latter part of next month.\nHenry Berry, dealer in Curios\nSpecialty, Ivory Beads. 165 Frott$\nStreet. \u2014adv.\n\nFurniture moved and stored i\nHeavy hauling done. Juneau Trans\n\u2019er. \u2014adv j\nALASKA MEAT COMPANY\nJOHN RECK, Manager. Wholesale and Retail Butch*\nBeef, Mutton, Pork, Chickens, Oysters, Fish, Home-Made Sanaa!\nHam and Bacon.\nSEWARD STREET.PHONE\na\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u00bb 1\n\u00a3'llllllll||||||||||||||||||t||||||||||||||tl|||||||||||t||||||||||||||||||||||||||H||||||||Hllllllt'4\nI AS FINE RUBBER GOODS\n1 AS THE WORLD PRODUCES J\ns\nDo vou know that a druggiit aelecta\nrubber quality exactly aa he aelecta\nfthg quality? Every hot watc*\nbottle or fountain ayringe or other\nrubber article in our atock ia per*\n_a. b _ _\nICCT in cveijr wajr rnauc ui utw, avuf\u00ab 55\nrubber. If it is the perfect goodi you want, s\nr buy here and know. fg\nBRITT\u2019S PH ARM ACIESj\nSeward Street Front Street\nlllllHIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIHIIIIIUIIIIIHIIItllUHMIllIttlHIlU.?\nL1\nHOW LONG SINCE YOUR WATCH\nWAS CLEANED?\nDon't wait for it to stop or you may spoil an\naccurate timekeeper.\nThis is the time of the year to have it over\nhauled tas we haxs leisure tim$ for those nice I\nfinishing touches that makes a perfect job.\nThe above refers aho to the family clock.\nWe would prefer to have you bring it here but\nfor the sake of a good timepiece take it some\nwhere.\nOROIH.,\nTHE NUGGET SHOP jj\nSIMPSON WRIGHT\niiiimiiiiiiimmimiiiiimiHimiimiiiimmiimiiiimiiiimiiiiiiiiimmimsiiiimii\nWE ARE OFFERING\nAll of the very best brands of\nCANNED GOODS\nat greatly\nReduced Prices\nt\nIf you cannot call and inspect our stock in\nperson, telephone us and we will\nquote you